2026-04-21 01:27:37 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power Supply Module output cables to Control Module 1 and their terminations on Control Module 1 input terminals'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules from Control Module 1 through the Load Module have been continuity‑tested and found correctly wired for both + and − lines, with no polarity inversion and ≈0.1 Ω continuity between each module’s corresponding in/out terminals. The load module and its internal diode/lamp network show normal continuity. The PSU has been verified to produce ~12 V between its two output terminals, with correct polarity, and its own indicator LED is lit. Yet 0.0 V is measured at the load module inputs, meaning the series path for 12 V is open somewhere between the PSU outputs and the rest of the chain.\n\nThe only segment that has not been explicitly continuity‑verified is the interface between the PSU output cables and Control Module 1’s input terminals (the external fast‑connection pair). The previous cabling tests referenced “PSU Output Cable (+) is continuous to Control Input Cable (+) 1 …” but the later detailed downstream tests show that all segments are continuous and correctly polarized while voltage at the load remains 0 V. This is consistent with a hidden open or mis‑termination precisely at the PSU–to–CM1 connection, such as:\n• the PSU output cables being plugged into the wrong connector pair on CM1, or\n• a bad/mis‑seated fast connector at CM1 so that continuity tests using certain reference points still saw the cable but the series circuit to the actual module input path is open.\n\nTherefore, the most probable fault is a configuration/connection error involving the PSU output cables and their terminations on Control Module 1’s input terminals. Repair would consist of correcting/ reseating this connection so that the verified 12 V from the PSU actually enters the series chain of control modules.'
