2026-04-21 01:27:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal series wiring / switch line within Control Module 2 between its input and output terminals'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that the Power Supply Module outputs a correct 12 V between its (+) and (−) terminals, and continuity/voltage tests confirm that this 12 V and 0 V are propagated correctly along all cabling from the PSU through Control Modules 1, 3–8, and into the Load Module. Despite this, the Load Module sees 0 V between its input terminals. This is only possible if there is an open circuit or internal disconnection in the series path somewhere that has not been seen in the cable tests.\n\nThe cabling tests from the PSU to Control Module 2 show 12 V present on the positive cables through to Control Input Cable (+) 3, and continuity of the negative line through Control Input Cable (−) 3. Downstream cabling from Control Module 3 to the Load Module is also continuous with correct polarity. Therefore, the only remaining location where the series path can be interrupted while preserving all the reported cabling continuities is inside Control Module 2 itself: specifically, between its positive input terminal and positive output terminal, or across its internal switch line. An open or miswired internal series connection in Control Module 2 would block current to all downstream modules, yielding 0 V at the Load Module and explaining why the lamp never energizes even though the PSU output is correct and all switches are ON.\n\nThus, the most plausible root cause is a fault in the internal series wiring or switch connection within Control Module 2 between its input and output terminals. Repairing or replacing this internal path should restore 12 V to the downstream modules and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are on.'
